-- FACTBOX-List of 91st Pulitzer Prizes
-- 
-- Mon Apr 16, 2007 5:41pm EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/04/16/us-media-pulitzers-facts-idUSN1633916220070416

 

 (Reuters) - The 91st annual Pulitzer Prizes in Journalism, Letters, Drama and Music were announced on Monday. 

 The following is a list of the winners: PUBLIC SERVICE -- The Wall Street Journal for its probe into backdated stock options for business executives that triggered investigations and the dismissal of senior figures in corporate America. BREAKING NEWS REPORTING -- The staff of the Oregonian, in Portland, Oregon, for its coverage of a family missing in the Oregon mountains. INVESTIGATIVE REPORTING -- Brett Blackledge of the Birmingham (Alabama) News for his exposure of cronyism and corruption in the state's two-year college system, which resulted in the dismissal of the chancellor. EXPLANATORY REPORTING -- Kenneth Weiss, Usha Lee McFarling and Rick Loomis of the Los Angeles Times for their reports on the world's distressed oceans. LOCAL REPORTING -- Debbie Cenziper of the Miami Herald for her reports on waste, favoritism and lack of oversight at the Miami housing agency. NATIONAL REPORTING -- Charlie Savage of the Boston Globe for his coverage of President George W. Bush's use of "signing statements" to assert his right to bypass provisions of new laws. INTERNATIONAL REPORTING -- The staff of the Wall Street Journal for its reports on the impact of China's booming capitalism. FEATURE WRITING -- Andrea Elliott of The New York Times for her portrait of an immigrant. COMMENTARY -- Cynthia Tucker of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution for her columns. CRITICISM -- Jonathan Gold of the LA Weekly for his restaurant reviews. EDITORIAL WRITING -- The editorial board of New York's Daily News for editorials on behalf of Ground Zero workers whose health problems were neglected. EDITORIAL CARTOONING -- Walt Handelsman of Newsday in Long Island, New York. BREAKING NEWS PHOTOGRAPHY -- Oded Balilty of the Associated Press for his photograph of a woman defying Israeli security forces as they removed illegal settlers in the West Bank. FEATURE PHOTOGRAPHY -- Renee Byer of the Sacramento Bee in California for her portrayal of a single mother and her young son as he was losing his battle with cancer. FICTION -- "The Road" by Cormac McCarthy, published by Alfred A. Knopf. DRAMA -- "Rabbit Hole" by David Lindsay-Abaire. HISTORY -- "The Race Beat: The Press, the Civil Rights Struggle, and the Awakening of a Nation" by Gene Roberts and Hank Klibanoff, published by Alfred A. Knopf. BIOGRAPHY OR AUTOBIOGRAPHY -- "The Most Famous Man in America: The Biography of Henry Ward Beecher" by Debby Applegate, published by Doubleday. POETRY -- "Native Guard" by Natasha Trethewey, published by Houghton Mifflin. GENERAL NON-FICTION -- "The Looming Tower: Al-Qaeda and the Road to 9/11" by Lawrence Wright, published by Alfred A. Knopf. MUSIC -- "Sound Grammar" by Ornette Coleman. SPECIAL CITATION -- John Coltrane. SPECIAL CITATION -- Ray Bradbury. (Reuters Messaging: ellen.wulfhorst.reuters.com@reuters.net)